lg.l: This is (say our Authors) when a Poet grows so very simple, as to think and talk like a Child; the Book to which the Discourse is prefix'd, affords us the following instances;

\following lines 154-55:\ A Sprig of a Flower is new and uncommon, People generally pluck the whole Flower; but if a single Sprig would serve, yet sure it could not be pluck'd from more than one Flower; a Sprig of Flowers is prodigious.
\following lines 242-45:\ This is such ingenious Prittle-Prattle, that the Author of it seems to be as hopeful an Infant as his own Vanessa.
Or, in plainer Words, downright Nonsense, which is no small part of the Profund, and of which great Plenty is to be found in their Writings.
\following lines 300-01:\ A Theme is a very odd Instrument to manage a Scheme with; as an abortive Scheme is in a very bad Condition to be managed.
Quere, What kind of Themes are the fittest for managing of Schemes, and whether the best won't come too late to manage a Scheme that is already abortive?
She pluck'd in Heaven's high Bow'rsSprig of Amaranthine Flow'rs.·p. 27
Miss Betty when she does a Fault,
Lets fall her Knife, or spills the Salt,
Will thus be by her Mother chid,
Nor shall Vanessa be the Theme
